    {
      "id": "1302898653836349460",
      "type": "Default",
      "timestamp": "2024-11-04T11:34:05.761+04:00",
      "timestampEdited": "2024-11-04T11:34:33.997+04:00",
      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "@LauriP no that's not the only reason. There are two different categories of reasons to use recursion:\n\n1. Enable larger computation. It doesn't necessarily have to be unbounded. Say you want to do the keccak hash of 1kB of data in your circuit - then that won't fit in a circuit, so you'll have to break it up into several recursive proofs. In this case, the computation isn't unbounded.\n\n2. Proofs should be created by different actors or by the same actor at different times. For example, the Mina node recursively composes zkapp proofs.",
      "author": {
